<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT/DTA-466 Diesel Engine Service (1990) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - CYLINDER SLEEVE
        REMOVAL - PISTON RINGS
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="4">
        <title>PISTON RINGS</title>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Faulty rings cannot always be detected by visual inspection. Therefore, whenever a piston is
                    removed from a cylinder, it is recommended that the piston rings be replaced.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Visually inspect NEW rings for cleanliness.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>All DTA and effective with S/N 532981 all DT-466 engines are equipped with offset crown top
                        compression rings. Refer to Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150620">6.20</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="ef4150619" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg11562" filename="../figcg1/cg11562.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.19. Measure Piston Skirt Diameter.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef4150620" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg11967" filename="../figcg1/cg11967.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.20. Standard vs. Offset Crown Top Compression Ring.</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Effective with S/N 589892 all DT/DTA-466 engines are equipped with a plasma-coated
                        offset-crown top compression ring and a plain-faced (chromeless) intermediate compression ring.
                        Individual compression rings are not serviced seperately and can only be obtained by ordering
                        the appropriate service package from the current parts catalog. Refer to Figures
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150621">6.21</hotlnk>
                        and
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150622">6.22</hotlnk>
                        for identification of rings.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="ef4150621" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg14594" filename="../figcg1/cg14594.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.21. Top Compression Ring Identification.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef4150622" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg14630" filename="../figcg1/cg14630.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.22. Intermediate Compression Ring Identification.</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Prior to installing the rings on the piston, check each ring for proper gap as follows:
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Push the ring down into the cylinder bore making sure the ring is square with the
                    cylinder wall.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Measure the gap between the ends of each ring with a feeler gauge as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk document="e415_111.xml" xrefid="ef4150623">6.23</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150601.xml" xrefid="hl4150601">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>
                    for ring gap. Discard any used ring which does not meet the specifications.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
